          <div align="left">
            <div align="justify">We are a research group at New York
              University, wishing to understand the foundations of
              generalization, learning, and decision making, towards building highly practical new methods in machine learning. Our work covers deep learning models, including LLMs, uncertainty representation, AI alignment, distribution shifts, physics inspired ML, equivariance modelling, numerical methods, and scientific discovery.
<!--We often (1) take a probabilistic
              approach; (2) care about automatically discovering
              scientifically interpretable structure in data; and (3)
              are excited about connections with physics, numerical methods and scientific computing. We are particularly active in building methods
              for Bayesian and probabilistic  deep learning, scalable Gaussian
              processes, kernel learning, geometric deep learning, physics-inspired deep learning, and training of deep neural
              networks.--> We believe in open and reproducible research. If
              you'd like to try out these methods check out our <a
                href="https://cims.nyu.edu/~andrewgw/code">code
                page</a>. See also our <a href="https://cims.nyu.edu/~andrewgw/join">info about joining</a>, which describes research interests and some example papers in greater detail. 

<!--
In more detail, our work builds cumulatively towards resolving several foundational questions:<br>
• <i>What are the general principles and prescriptions for model construction?</i>  <br>
• <i>How do we select between hypotheses that are entirely consistent with any amount of data we observe?</i><br>
• <i>How do we develop an actionable understanding of deep neural networks?</i>  <br>
• <i>How do we resolve kernel selection and scalability for Gaussian processes?</i><br>
• <i>How can we exploit algebraic structure (e.g., for scalable inference) arising from popular modelling assumptions?</i><br>
• <i>How can we make models robust to distribution shifts that preserve semantic structure?</i><br>
• <i>Can representation learning be used to make new scientific discoveries?</i><br>
• <i>Does there have to be a trade-off between flexibility and inductive biases?</i><br>
• <i> How can a model automatically discover fundamental symmetries such as translation equivariance?</i><br>
<br>
